The significant morphological differences between the new species and its continental neighbor are likely due to its isolation from the African mainland populations, separated by the Gabon Basin with depths of 2000–3500 m and a horizontal distance of between 200–250 km . São Tomé & Príncipe , while geographically close to the continent, has been isolated from the mainland since the initial oceanic archipelago formed in the Oligocene, around 31 million years ago (
Lee et al . 1994
).
